5 allow the witness to testify at the preliminary examination through the use of
6 audiovisual technology.
7 2. If a witness testifies at the preliminary examination through the use of
8 audiovisual technology:
9 (a) The testimony of the witness must be transcribed by a certified court
10 reporter; [and]
11 (b) Before [At least 10 days before] giving testimony, the witness must [be
12 sworn and must] sign a sworn, written declaration, on a form provided by the
13 magistrate, which acknowledges that the witness understands that he or she is
14 subject to the jurisdiction of the courts of this State and may be subject to criminal
15 prosecution for the commission of any crime in connection with his or her
16 testimony, including, without limitation, perjury, and that the witness consents to
17 such jurisdiction [. The declaration must be filed with the court as soon as
18 practicable but not] ; and
19 (c) Not later than [5 days] 48 hours before the time set for the preliminary
20 examination , [. Together with the declaration,] the State [shall] must file with the
21 court both the declaration and a notice stating [the reason why] whether it is
22 necessary for the witness to testify at the preliminary examination through the
23 use of audiovisual technology [.] because the witness:
24 (1) Resides more than 100 miles from the place of the preliminary
25 examination; or
26 (2) Is unable to attend the preliminary examination because of a medical
27 condition.
28 3. Audiovisual technology used pursuant to this section must ensure that the
29 witness may be:
30 (a) Clearly heard and seen; and
31 (b) Examined and cross-examined.
32 4. As used in this section, “audiovisual technology” includes, without
33 limitation, closed-circuit video and videoconferencing.
